00:40:08.410 --> 00:40:11.890
I do a lot of yoga and
meditation, so I use that in

00:40:11.890 --> 00:40:12.690
the airplane.

00:40:12.690 --> 00:40:16.530
That's what I also used
when I did my 72-hour

00:40:16.530 --> 00:40:18.390
flight in the simulator.

00:40:18.390 --> 00:40:22.000
Bertrand is using other
techniques for that that he'll

00:40:22.000 --> 00:40:24.700
certainly use when he does
his training in the

00:40:24.700 --> 00:40:27.070
simulator this fall.

00:40:27.070 --> 00:40:30.720
So that's how we think we try
to cope with these questions

00:40:30.720 --> 00:40:33.720
and not using substance.

00:40:33.720 --> 00:40:35.320
AUDIENCE: Someone's asking, "The
weather is a major factor

00:40:35.320 --> 00:40:37.430
in planning in around
the world flights.

00:40:37.430 --> 00:40:40.200
Please talk about how you're
planning on doing it." And I

00:40:40.200 --> 00:40:42.740
guess a follow up question that
goes together for me is,

00:40:42.740 --> 00:40:45.730
if your plane does 25 knots,
with a good wet headwind,

00:40:45.730 --> 00:40:47.560
you'll actually be going
backwards, unless you're

00:40:47.560 --> 00:40:50.440
flying with a jet stream going
eastbound and taking it.

00:40:50.440 --> 00:40:52.460
ANDRE BORSCHBERG: We have the
man who has the record flying

00:40:52.460 --> 00:40:55.880
backwards next to me--

00:40:55.880 --> 00:40:58.360
the world record!

00:40:58.360 --> 00:41:00.200
BERTRAND PICCARD: Well, it's
true, when I came back from

00:41:00.200 --> 00:41:05.240
Morocco to Spain, I was not
allowed to arrive in Madrid

00:41:05.240 --> 00:41:06.630
before midnight because of

00:41:06.630 --> 00:41:10.250
international commercial airline.

00:41:10.250 --> 00:41:13.240
So if I was going with the
winds, I would have

00:41:13.240 --> 00:41:14.840
come far too early.

00:41:14.840 --> 00:41:15.980
And then waiting there, I would

00:41:15.980 --> 00:41:18.350
have drifted to Barcelona.

00:41:18.350 --> 00:41:22.580
So the team sent me on another
path to Portugal, on low

00:41:22.580 --> 00:41:24.540
level, and asked me to climb.

00:41:24.540 --> 00:41:28.670
And then I was headwind with a
wind that was faster than me.

00:41:28.670 --> 00:41:31.040
And I drifted back to Madrid.

00:41:31.040 --> 00:41:34.160
I was facing a beautiful sunset
to the west, and I was

00:41:34.160 --> 00:41:35.260
drifting through the east.

00:41:35.260 --> 00:41:37.970
So it was a perfect way to do.

00:41:37.970 --> 00:41:39.060
But it's quite strange.

00:41:39.060 --> 00:41:41.970
In the beginning, you just have
to understand that to

00:41:41.970 --> 00:41:45.660
follow your line on the GPS,
you have to turn left to go

00:41:45.660 --> 00:41:47.960
right and to turn right
to go left.

00:41:47.960 --> 00:41:50.350
And once you understand
that, it's fine then.

00:41:50.350 --> 00:41:51.355
[LAUGHING]

00:41:51.355 --> 00:41:53.720
BERTRAND PICCARD: But you just
have also to cope with the

00:41:53.720 --> 00:41:57.610
anxiety of the guys in
the control center.

00:41:57.610 --> 00:41:59.720
AUDIENCE: Is it fair to say that
basically, even though

00:41:59.720 --> 00:42:02.610
you're not flying a balloon, you
have 25 knots of airspeed,

00:42:02.610 --> 00:42:05.000
or really, when you're
at 25,000 feet, it's

00:42:05.000 --> 00:42:06.020
not airspeed at all.

00:42:06.020 --> 00:42:08.850
So are you just following the
jet stream and any kind of

00:42:08.850 --> 00:42:10.520
weather pattern that will
push you to where

00:42:10.520 --> 00:42:12.050
you're trying to get.

00:42:12.050 --> 00:42:14.320
ANDRE BORSCHBERG: We
try to avoid them

00:42:14.320 --> 00:42:15.650
because they may be turbulent.

00:42:15.650 --> 00:42:19.070
And we try to get the good
meteorology, which is a

00:42:19.070 --> 00:42:20.230
certain meteorology.

00:42:20.230 --> 00:42:22.570
So that's not necessarily where
the jet streams are.

00:42:22.570 --> 00:42:25.050
So maybe we have them,
maybe not, but it's

00:42:25.050 --> 00:42:26.840
not the goal by itself.

00:42:26.840 --> 00:42:29.430
And if you look at the
Pacific, normally the

00:42:29.430 --> 00:42:33.710
situation is such that the wind
at the upper level of

00:42:33.710 --> 00:42:35.370
west to east--

00:42:35.370 --> 00:42:36.300
favorable.

00:42:36.300 --> 00:42:40.270
But you have the trade winds,
which are at low altitudes, at

00:42:40.270 --> 00:42:43.200
about flight level 100, which
are on the other side.

00:42:43.200 --> 00:42:48.580
So what we may do and may
experience is to fly forward

00:42:48.580 --> 00:42:50.710
during the day when we climb
and backwards and

00:42:50.710 --> 00:42:51.930
be during the night.

00:42:51.930 --> 00:42:55.980
And hopefully, the daily flight
is going to be a bit

00:42:55.980 --> 00:42:57.260
longer than the night flight.

00:42:57.260 --> 00:42:57.660
[LAUGHING]

00:42:57.660 --> 00:42:59.690
BERTRAND PICCARD: And the result
is that maybe when I

00:42:59.690 --> 00:43:04.350
flew around the world in my
balloon, it took less time

00:43:04.350 --> 00:43:06.830
than what we're going to
do with our plane.

00:43:06.830 --> 00:43:08.740
Because with a balloon, you
put yourself in the jet

00:43:08.740 --> 00:43:10.660
stream, the c the jet stream.

00:43:10.660 --> 00:43:13.540
You stay up day and night.

00:43:13.540 --> 00:43:17.440
And the average speed
around the world was

00:43:17.440 --> 00:43:19.710
60 miles per hour.

00:43:19.710 --> 00:43:19.910
AUDIENCE: [WHISTLES]

00:43:19.910 --> 00:43:22.400
OK.

00:43:22.400 --> 00:43:26.370
BERTRAND PICCARD: The fastest
parts over the Atlantic was

00:43:26.370 --> 00:43:28.780
234 kilometers per hour.

00:43:28.780 --> 00:43:29.200
AUDIENCE: [WHISTLES]

00:43:29.200 --> 00:43:30.990
BERTRAND PICCARD: That's
131 knots.

00:43:30.990 --> 00:43:34.250
It's 160 miles per hour--

00:43:34.250 --> 00:43:36.270
165 miles per hour.

00:43:36.270 --> 00:43:37.910
Fortunately no speed limit.

00:43:37.910 --> 00:43:39.550
[LAUGHING]

00:43:39.550 --> 00:43:42.273
AUDIENCE: So the next question
that's also related is, "How

00:43:42.273 --> 00:43:44.570
long do you expect the flight
around the world to take?"

00:43:44.570 --> 00:43:46.740
Which is also related to,
do you have a route?

00:43:46.740 --> 00:43:49.740
Do you know what you're
expecting to be doing?

00:43:49.740 --> 00:43:53.630
ANDRE BORSCHBERG: So close to
the balloon flight in the end.

00:43:53.630 --> 00:43:55.830
So about 20 flying days.

00:43:55.830 --> 00:43:58.730
It can be more, it can be less--
it depends on the wind.

00:43:58.730 --> 00:44:02.450
But this will be spread over
a certain period of time.

00:44:02.450 --> 00:44:06.520
Because we'll be landing in
the larger countries.

00:44:06.520 --> 00:44:09.800
And everywhere where we land
there is a strong interest.

00:44:09.800 --> 00:44:12.360
Right now, when we do our
stops through the United

00:44:12.360 --> 00:44:15.450
States, there is an interest for
